The parallel to the 2008 New South Wales coup is that in the week following the coup, the Supreme Court declared it illegal, the military withdrew, government services were restored in practice. In order to defeat the coup, the parliament re-passed a new constitution, significantly impinging head of government power. The 2014 coup has distinct parallels to 1966 and yet with one significant exception. Unlike 1966 when elected governments were replaced with military dictatorships, in 2014 the elected government was replaced by a short lived caretaker government. In 1966, the military came straight to power; in 2014, the military stayed out. In 2014, government services were restored.
It is worth noting that in 1966 and 2006 governments of the day were at war with Marxist thugs, the United Suva Merchants Association, the Women’s Association and the Maloko Magoniu Usifoa Kedroi (translated adviser of Pacific Affairs) respectively (Drell, 2003, p. 45), who were backed by riots in the course of the coups.
